# JPA / Hibernate — Learned Concepts

---

## How Hibernate Tackles the Inheritance Mismatch

Object-Oriented Java supports inheritance naturally — a `Car` can extend `Vehicle`, an `Admin` can extend `User`. But relational databases have no concept of inheritance; they only know tables and rows. This is called the **Object-Relational Impedance Mismatch**.

Hibernate solves this by providing **3 inheritance mapping strategies**, each a different way of flattening the OOP hierarchy into tables.

---

## Strategy 1 — SINGLE_TABLE (`InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE`)

### How it works
All classes in the hierarchy share **one single table**. A special **discriminator column** tells Hibernate which subtype each row belongs to.

### Annotations
```java
// Parent
@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)
@DiscriminatorColumn(name = "user_type", discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)

// Child
@DiscriminatorValue("ADMIN")
```

### Tables created
```
users
---------------------------------------------------------
id | name | email | user_type | department | accessLevel | shippingAddress | loyaltyTier
---------------------------------------------------------
1  | Suraj | ...  | ADMIN     | Engineering| 5           | NULL            | NULL
2  | John  | ...  | CUSTOMER  | NULL       | NULL        | Rockdale        | 1122A
```

### Pros & Cons
| ✅ Pro | ❌ Con |
|--------|--------|
| Simplest, fastest queries — no joins | Subclass columns are nullable (can't enforce NOT NULL) |
| Only one table to manage | Table gets wide with many subtypes |

---

## Strategy 2 — JOINED (`InheritanceType.JOINED`)

### How it works
The **parent entity has its own table** with shared fields. Each **subclass has its own table** with only its extra fields. They are linked via the **primary key as a foreign key**.

### Annotations
```java
// Parent
@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.JOINED)

// Child
@Table(name = "cars")  // each child gets its own table
```

### Tables created
```
vehicles                    cars                        motorcycles
--------------------        --------------------        ----------------------
id | brand | year | price   id | numberOfDoors | body   id | motorcycleType | hasSidecar
--------------------        --------------------        ----------------------
1  | Toyota| 2022 | 35000   1  | 4             | SUV
2  | Harley| 2021 | 20000                               2  | cruiser        | false
```

The `id` in `cars` and `motorcycles` is both the **primary key AND a foreign key** back to `vehicles`.

### Query Hibernate runs under the hood
```sql
SELECT v.*, c.*
FROM vehicles v
INNER JOIN cars c ON v.id = c.id
WHERE v.id = ?
```

### Pros & Cons
| ✅ Pro | ❌ Con |
|--------|--------|
| Fully normalized, no nulls | Every query costs a JOIN |
| Clean schema, easy to add constraints | Slightly more complex schema |

---

## Strategy 3 — TABLE_PER_CLASS (`InheritanceType.TABLE_PER_CLASS`)

### How it works
**No shared parent table.** Each concrete subclass gets its **own complete table** containing ALL fields — both parent and child fields duplicated. The parent class itself holds no data.

### Annotations
```java
// Parent — must be abstract
@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.TABLE_PER_CLASS)

// IMPORTANT: Must use SEQUENCE, not IDENTITY
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
```

### Tables created
```
full_time_employees                         contract_employees
----------------------------------------------  ----------------------------------------
id | name  | email | baseSalary | annualLeaves | benefits  id | name | email | baseSalary | contractDuration | agency
----------------------------------------------  ----------------------------------------
1  | Alice | ...   | 90000      | 20           | Health    2  | Bob  | ...   | 75000      | 6 months         | TechStaff
```

Notice: `name`, `email`, `baseSalary` are **duplicated** in both tables (copied from parent).

### Why SEQUENCE not IDENTITY?
`IDENTITY` is per-table auto-increment. If both tables use it independently, you'd get `FullTimeEmployee id=1` AND `ContractEmployee id=1` — collision when Hibernate does polymorphic UNION queries. `SEQUENCE` uses a **centralized counter** (Hibernate creates a `employee_seq` table) to ensure IDs are globally unique.

### The sequence table
```sql
SELECT * FROM employee_seq;
-- next_val = 101
```
Hibernate pre-allocates IDs in **batches of 50** (default). `next_val = 101` means it has already reserved IDs 1–100 in memory. To change this:
```java
@SequenceGenerator(name = "emp_gen", sequenceName = "employee_seq", allocationSize = 1)
```

### Polymorphic queries use UNION
```sql
-- Querying the parent type fetches ALL subtypes with UNION
SELECT * FROM full_time_employees
UNION ALL
SELECT * FROM contract_employees
```

### Pros & Cons
| ✅ Pro | ❌ Con |
|--------|--------|
| No joins for subtype-specific queries | Parent fields duplicated across all tables |
| Clean per-type tables | Polymorphic queries are slow (UNION) |

---

## Summary Comparison

| | SINGLE_TABLE | JOINED | TABLE_PER_CLASS |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Tables created** | 1 (everything) | 1 parent + N children | N children only |
| **Join needed?** | No | Yes (per query) | No (but UNION for polymorphic) |
| **Discriminator column?** | Yes (required) | Optional | No |
| **Nullable subclass columns?** | Yes | No | No |
| **ID strategy** | IDENTITY ok | IDENTITY ok | Needs SEQUENCE |
| **Best for** | Simple hierarchies, read-heavy | Normalized schemas, few subtypes | Isolated subtypes, rare polymorphic queries |

